			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The courts of appeals are creatures of statute. <eos/>
						<bos/>Their jurisdiction extends only to matters authorized by Congress.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Statutes defining that jurisdiction are numerous.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="Iceef3bd08ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">1</footnote.reference>] The most common is the jurisdiction to review a final decision by a federal district court—the so-called final judgment rule.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="Iceef62e08ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">2</footnote.reference>] District courts may certify certain decisions as final.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="Iceef62e18ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">3</footnote.reference>] Statutes also authorize certain interlocutory appeals as a matter of right,[<footnote.reference refid="Icef222008ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">4</footnote.reference>] or when permitted by the district court and court of appeals.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="Icef222018ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">5</footnote.reference>] Courts of appeals may also review district court actions via extraordinary writ.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="Icef333718ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">6</footnote.reference>] In cases specified by statute, courts of appeals may also review decisions by magistrate[<footnote.reference refid="Icef333728ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">7</footnote.reference>] and bankruptcy judges.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="Icef35a808ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Courts of appeals also have jurisdiction to review final decisions by the U.S. Tax Court,[<footnote.reference refid="Icef35a818ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">9</footnote.reference>] and to review or enforce certain actions by federal agencies.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="Icef5cb818ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>As courts of limited jurisdiction, the courts of appeals must inquire into their own jurisdiction even if the parties do not. <eos/>
						<bos/>Parties cannot concede appellate jurisdiction, create it by stipulation, or waive defects to it. <eos/>
						<bos/>If a court lacks jurisdiction, it has no authority to consider the merits.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Most procedures in the courts of appeals are governed by the Federal Rules of Appellate Procedure, an outgrowth of earlier parts of the Federal Rules of Civil and Criminal Procedure. <eos/>
						<bos/>The Federal Rules of Appellate Procedure took effect in 1968.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="Icef6dcf08ed311eab3efd3209dce8855">11</footnote.reference>] The final chapter in this volume illustrates forms used in procedures not covered by these rules.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
